#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:10
msgid "3.3 Contrastive Divergence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:12
msgid ""
"Section [3.2 The Intractable Partition Function Problem](kpp-theoretical-"
"foundations-ebms-partition.md) established that exact maximum likelihood "
"learning of Boltzmann machines is computationally infeasible due to the "
"intractable partition function. The model expectation term in the "
"gradient requires sampling from the equilibrium distribution $P_\\theta$,"
" which in turn demands running a Markov chain to convergence, which is a "
"prohibitively slow process. In this section, we introduce **contrastive "
"divergence (CD)**, the algorithmic breakthrough that made Boltzmann "
"machines practical for real-world applications. CD provides a simple, "
"efficient approximation to the gradient that circumvents the need for "
"equilibrium sampling, trading theoretical purity for empirical "
"effectiveness."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:14
msgid "The Core Insight: Truncated Markov Chains"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:15
msgid ""
"The key observation behind contrastive divergence, introduced by Geoffrey"
" Hinton in 2002, is that we need not run the Markov chain all the way to "
"equilibrium. Instead, we can initialize the chain at a **data point** and"
" run it for only a small number of steps, often just **one,** and then "
"treat the resulting state as an approximate sample from the model "
"distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:17
msgid ""
"Why should this work? Consider the gradient of the negative log-"
"likelihood:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:19
msgid ""
"\\nabla f(\\theta) = -\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}} \\left[ \\frac{\\partial"
" E_\\theta}{\\partial \\theta} \\right] + \\mathbb{E}_{\\text{model}} "
"\\left[ \\frac{\\partial E_\\theta}{\\partial \\theta} \\right]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:21
msgid ""
"The first term is an expectation over the data distribution, which is "
"easy to compute. But the second term requires sampling from the model "
"distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:23
msgid ""
"In contrastive divergence, we replace the model expectation with an "
"expectation over a distribution obtained after $k$ steps of Gibbs "
"sampling initialized from the data, yielding the **CD-k** update rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:25
msgid ""
"\\Delta \\theta \\propto -\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}} \\left[ "
"\\frac{\\partial E_\\theta}{\\partial \\theta} \\right] + "
"\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{recon after } k \\text{ steps}} \\left[ "
"\\frac{\\partial E_\\theta}{\\partial \\theta} \\right]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:27
msgid ""
"Note that this is equivalent to the standard CD update $\\Delta w_{ij} = "
"\\eta (\\langle v_i h_j \\rangle_{\\text{data}} - \\langle v_i h_j "
"\\rangle_{\\text{recon}})$ because $\\frac{\\partial E_\\theta}{\\partial"
" w_{ij}} = -v_i h_j$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:29
msgid ""
"The intuition is that the Markov chain, even after a few steps, moves "
"away from the data distribution toward the model distribution. The "
"difference between the data statistics and the statistics after $k$ steps"
" approximates the true gradient direction. Remarkably, for $k = 1$, this "
"simple heuristic works well enough to train useful generative models."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:31
msgid "The CD-k Algorithm in Detail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:32
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The CD-k algorithm for training a Restricted Boltzmann Machine (RBM) or a"
" general Boltzmann machine proceeds as follows: **Algorithm: Contrastive "
"Divergence (CD-k)** For each training example $\\mathbf{v}^{(0)}$ (the "
"visible state):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:34
msgid "**Positive Phase**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:35
#, python-brace-format
msgid "Clamp the visible units to the data vector $\\mathbf{v}^{(0)}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:36
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Compute the hidden unit activations $P(\\mathbf{h} \\mid "
"\\mathbf{v}^{(0)})$ and sample a binary hidden state $\\mathbf{h}^{(0)}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:37
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Record the outer product $\\mathbf{v}^{(0)} (\\mathbf{h}^{(0)})^\\top$ as"
" the **positive statistics**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:39
msgid "**Negative Phase** (Gibbs sampling for $k$ steps):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:40
msgid "For $t = 1$ to $k$:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:41
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Sample visible reconstruction $ \\mathbf{v}^{(t)} \\sim P(\\mathbf{v} "
"\\mid \\mathbf{h}^{(t-1)})$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:42
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Sample hidden reconstruction $\\mathbf{h}^{(t)} \\sim P(\\mathbf{h} \\mid"
" \\mathbf{v}^{(t)})$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:43
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Record the outer product $\\mathbf{v}^{(k)} (\\mathbf{h}^{(k)})^\\top$ as"
" the **negative statistics**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:45
msgid "**Weight Update**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:47
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Update each weight $w_{ij}$ using the difference between positive and "
"negative statistics:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:49
msgid ""
"\\Delta w_{ij} = \\eta \\left( \\langle v_i h_j \\rangle_{\\text{data}} -"
" \\langle v_i h_j \\rangle_{\\text{recon}} \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:51
msgid ""
"where $\\eta$ is the learning rate. Biases are updated similarly using "
"unit activations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:53
msgid ""
"For **CD-1** (the most common variant), the negative phase consists of a "
"single round-trip:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:55
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"$\\mathbf{v}^{(0)} \\rightarrow \\mathbf{h}^{(0)} \\rightarrow "
"\\mathbf{v}^{(1)} \\rightarrow \\mathbf{h}^{(1)}$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:57
msgid "Geometric Interpretation: Approximating the Gradient"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:58
msgid ""
"The contrastive divergence update can be understood geometrically. The "
"true gradient of the log-likelihood points in the direction that reduces "
"the energy of data configurations and increases the energy of "
"configurations that the model currently deems probable. CD approximates "
"this by comparing the data configurations to nearby **reconstructions**, "
"which are configurations obtained by following the Markov chain a short "
"distance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:60
msgid ""
"Consider the energy landscape. The data points sit in (or near) basins of"
" low energy. Running Gibbs sampling for a few steps moves the state "
"slightly away from the data, typically toward regions of higher energy if"
" the model has not yet fully learned the data distribution. The CD update"
" pushes the energy **down** at the data point and **up** at the nearby "
"reconstruction. This effectively deepens the basin around the data while "
"raising the energy of the surrounding region, creating a steeper "
"attractor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:62
msgid ""
"Crucially, CD does **not** attempt to raise the energy of *all* other "
"configurations equally. It focuses only on those configurations that are "
"easily reachable from the data via short MCMC trajectories. This local "
"contrast is sufficient to learn a good model in practice, even though it "
"introduces a bias relative to the true maximum likelihood gradient."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:64
msgid "Why Contrastive Divergence Works: A Heuristic Justification"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:65
msgid ""
"The empirical success of CD, especially CD-1, initially surprised many "
"researchers. Several lines of reasoning help explain its effectiveness:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:67
msgid ""
"**Initialization at Data**: By starting the Markov chain at data points, "
"we are sampling from regions of high data density. If the model "
"distribution is already close to the data distribution, the chain will "
"mix quickly, and a few steps suffice. If the model is far from the data, "
"the chain moves away rapidly, providing a strong contrast signal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:68
msgid ""
"**Gradient of the KL Divergence**: It can be shown that CD-k minimizes a "
"different objective function: the difference between two Kullback-Leibler"
" divergences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:70
msgid ""
"\\text{CD}_k = \\text{KL}(P_{\\text{data}} \\| P_\\theta) - "
"\\text{KL}(P_\\theta^{(k)} \\| P_\\theta)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:72
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $P_\\theta^{(k)}$ is the distribution after $k$ steps of MCMC "
"starting from the data. Minimizing this **contrastive divergence** "
"encourages the model distribution to be close to the data distribution "
"while simultaneously being far from the $k$ step distribution. This "
"formulation justifies the name and provides a more principled foundation "
"than a mere heuristic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:74
msgid ""
"**Persistent Contrastive Divergence (PCD)**: An important variant, "
"**persistent contrastive divergence**, maintains a persistent set of "
"Markov chains whose states are retained across weight updates. Instead of"
" reinitializing from data each time, the chains continue to evolve. PCD "
"yields samples that are closer to the true model distribution and can "
"improve the quality of the learned model, especially for deeper "
"architectures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:76
msgid "Limitations and Caveats"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:77
msgid ""
"Contrastive divergence is a pragmatic approximation, not an exact "
"algorithm. It has several known limitations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:79
msgid ""
"**Bias**: CD does not produce an unbiased estimate of the true log-"
"likelihood gradient. The bias can be large for small $k$, and the "
"resulting parameter estimates are not maximum likelihood estimates. The "
"learned model may not assign the highest possible likelihood to the data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:80
msgid ""
"**Not a Proper Gradient of Any Function**: For $k > 1$, the CD update is "
"not the gradient of any fixed objective function. This makes theoretical "
"analysis difficult and complicates convergence monitoring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:81
msgid ""
"**Mixing and Mode Collapse**: If the model distribution has widely "
"separated modes, short MCMC runs starting from data may fail to explore "
"the full landscape, leading to mode collapse—the model learns only a "
"subset of the data distribution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:82
msgid ""
"**Dependence on k**: Larger values of $k$ reduce bias but increase "
"computational cost. In practice, CD-1 or CD-5 are common compromises."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:84
msgid ""
"Despite these limitations, contrastive divergence remains a cornerstone "
"algorithm for training restricted Boltzmann machines and deep belief "
"networks. Its simplicity, speed, and empirical effectiveness enabled the "
"mid-2000s renaissance of deep learning based on layer-wise pretraining."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:86
msgid "From Contrastive Divergence to Modern Approximations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:87
msgid ""
"The success of CD inspired a family of related algorithms that improve "
"upon its limitations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:89
msgid ""
"**Persistent Contrastive Divergence (PCD)**: Uses persistent Markov "
"chains to obtain better negative samples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:90
msgid ""
"**Fast Persistent Contrastive Divergence (FPCD)**: Introduces additional "
"fast-learning weights to improve mixing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:91
msgid ""
"**Parallel Tempering**: Runs multiple chains at different temperatures to"
" overcome energy barriers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:92
msgid ""
"**Score Matching and Noise Contrastive Estimation**: Bypass the need for "
"MCMC entirely, as mentioned in Section [3.2 The Intractable Partition "
"Function Problem](kpp-theoretical-foundations-ebms-partition.md)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:94
msgid ""
"These methods represent the ongoing evolution of techniques for training "
"energy-based models, all stemming from the fundamental insight that we "
"can trade exactness for tractability in learning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:96
msgid "Practical Implementation: Mini-Batches and Sampling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:97
msgid ""
"In practice, the expectation $\\mathbb{E}_{\\text{data}}$ is not computed"
" over the full dataset, but over a **mini-batch** of $M$ samples. This "
"reduces computational cost and provides a stochastic gradient that can "
"often escape local minima. Typical mini-batch sizes range from 10 to 100."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:99
msgid ""
"For the Gibbs sampling in the negative phase, you will usually run the "
"chain for $k$ steps (often $k=1$) starting from the data. This is the "
"Contrastive Divergence-$k$ (CD-$k$) algorithm. While not strictly "
"following the gradient of the log-likelihood, it works well in practice. "
"When implementing the update, the weight change for a mini-batch becomes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:101
msgid ""
"\\Delta \\mathbf{W} = \\frac{\\eta}{M} \\sum_{m=1}^M \\left( \\langle "
"\\mathbf{v}^{(m)} (\\mathbf{h}^{(m)})^\\top \\rangle_{\\text{data}} - "
"\\langle \\mathbf{v}^{(m)}_k (\\mathbf{h}^{(m)}_k)^\\top "
"\\rangle_{\\text{recon}} \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:103
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $\\mathbf{v}^{(m)}_k, \\mathbf{h}^{(m)}_k$ are the final states "
"after $k$ Gibbs steps. Using mini-batches is crucial for scaling to large"
" datasets like MNIST or ImageNet. **Efficiency tip**: In code (especially"
" Python), try to vectorize the computation over the entire mini-batch "
"using matrix operations rather than looping over individual examples. "
"This can lead to orders-of-magnitude speedups."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:105
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:106
msgid ""
"**Contrastive divergence (CD)** is a practical approximation to the "
"maximum likelihood gradient for training Boltzmann machines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:107
msgid ""
"CD replaces the model expectation with an expectation over a **short "
"Markov chain** initialized at the data, typically running for only $k$ "
"steps (often $k=1$)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:108
msgid ""
"The CD-k algorithm alternates between a **positive phase** (clamped to "
"data) and a **negative phase** (brief free-running reconstruction)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:109
msgid ""
"Geometrically, CD deepens the energy basin at data points while raising "
"energy in their immediate MCMC-accessible neighborhood."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:110
msgid ""
"CD minimizes a **difference of KL divergences** rather than the negative "
"log-likelihood directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:111
msgid ""
"Limitations include **bias**, lack of a proper objective function for $ "
"k>1$, and potential **mode collapse**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:112
msgid ""
"**Persistent contrastive divergence (PCD)** improves sampling quality by "
"maintaining persistent Markov chains across updates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:113
msgid ""
"**Mini-batch training** and **vectorization** are key practical "
"considerations for efficient implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/theoretical-foundations-ebms-cd.md:114
msgid ""
"CD enabled the practical training of RBMs and deep belief networks, "
"playing a pivotal role in the deep learning renaissance of the 2000s."
msgstr ""

